.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
In basic use without specifying a locale, a formatted string in the
default locale and with default options is returned.
This is useful to distinguish between singular and plural forms,
e.g.\ \[lq]dog\[rq] and \[lq]dogs\[rq].
.IP
.EX
const pr = new Intl.PluralRules();

pr.select(0); // \[aq]other\[aq] if in US English locale

pr.select(1); // \[aq]one\[aq] if in US English locale

pr.select(2); // \[aq]other\[aq] if in US English locale
.EE
.SS Using options
The results can be customized using the \f[CR]options\f[R] argument,
which has one property called \f[CR]type\f[R] which you can set to
\f[CR]ordinal\f[R].
This is useful to figure out the ordinal indicator, e.g.\ \[lq]1st\[rq],
\[lq]2nd\[rq], \[lq]3rd\[rq], \[lq]4th\[rq], \[lq]42nd\[rq], and so
forth.
.IP
.EX
const pr = new Intl.PluralRules(\[dq]en-US\[dq], { type: \[dq]ordinal\[dq] });

const suffixes = new Map([
  [\[dq]one\[dq], \[dq]st\[dq]],
  [\[dq]two\[dq], \[dq]nd\[dq]],
  [\[dq]few\[dq], \[dq]rd\[dq]],
  [\[dq]other\[dq], \[dq]th\[dq]],
]);
const formatOrdinals = (n) => {
  const rule = pr.select(n);
  const suffix = suffixes.get(rule);
  return \[ga]${n}${suffix}\[ga];
};

formatOrdinals(0); // \[aq]0th\[aq]
formatOrdinals(1); // \[aq]1st\[aq]
formatOrdinals(2); // \[aq]2nd\[aq]
formatOrdinals(3); // \[aq]3rd\[aq]
formatOrdinals(4); // \[aq]4th\[aq]
formatOrdinals(11); // \[aq]11th\[aq]
formatOrdinals(21); // \[aq]21st\[aq]
formatOrdinals(42); // \[aq]42nd\[aq]
formatOrdinals(103); // \[aq]103rd\[aq]
.EE
